ODE III.

Augustus had desired Horace to write two odes3 one upon the Secular games3 and the other upon the conquests of Drusus and Tiberius in Pannonia. The poet commences this ode with the praises of Drusus, as it was his first campaign, and as he was more beloved by Augustus than Tiberius. In the XIIIth ode of this book he continues the subject principally in praise of Tiberius.

18. Quibus (sc. Vindelicis) . . . distuli: it is matter of doubt to commentators how these four verses came here. All admit them to be unworthy of the poet, and brought in without apparent rea- son. Some suppose it may have been a common question, when talking of the conquests of Drusus, from whence the Vindelici de· rived the custom of arming themselves with axes, like the Amazons. Others think they may have been written in ridicule of some other poet, who had attempted to celebrate the same con- quests, and used some such language.

24. Consiliis . . . revictce .- ‘ vanquished by the wisdom of this· youthful prince.' '

28. In pueros . . . Nerones .· ‚Tiberius and Drusus were the sons of Tiberius Nero by Livia. When Augustus married their mother, Livia, he adopted Tiberius and Drusus 3 and brought them up with the same tenderness and care that he would have done, had they been his own children.

35. Utcunque . . . culpae .- ‘ whenever good precepts are wanting, vices obscure the natural endowments.’
